result.execSummary:
The defendant Joanna D. Roybal was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Attorney Poss appeared on behalf of the defendant.  Victim is present.   $44.96 for mileage request stipulated to.   Attorney Poss objects to the amount of the door.  Exhibit 1 marked.  Offered by State.  Photos of door jam.  Court viewed.  Poss contends the door would be a civil action.  Amount is excessive.  Victim sworn, testified.  State questioned.  Attorney Poss questioned.  Court addressed State v. Lee.  Proper remedy is civil/small claims action.  Restitution ordered:  $44.96.
Restitution hearing at 08-04-2015 01:30 pm
DNA submission form
Destroyed fingerprint cards and sent copy of mintues to J.O. to schedule restitution hearing

Defendant appeared with counsel SPD Carly Sebion, who appeared specially for William Poss.  DA Gerald Fox appears for the State.  State has complied with victim notification.  A restitution request has been filed but defense is disputing.  There is a joint recommmendation that the defendant will plead to Count 2 with sentence withheld and placed on probation for 1 year with conditions.  Judge reviews charge in Count 2; defendant enters a plea of no contest.  Court reviews elements/PLQ/WOR.  Court finds she understands the proceedings; plea is made freely, voluntarily, and intelligently; waives rights freely and voluntarily; factual basis exists is found guilty of Count 2.  Counts 1 & 3 are dismissed and read-in.  Joint recommendation for 1 year probation adopted and ordered with following conditions ordered:  The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  Must pay the costs of the action.  Defendant may apply for expungement if probation successfully completed and all court obligations are satisfied.  Court grants 4 days jail credit.  Restitution will remain open as the $544.96 is disputed and will be scheduled for a restitution hearing for 1/2 hour.  Carly Sebion will schedule with J.A.  Defendant's address is correct.
